#### Terms defined in Metasploit UI ####

- Exploit: A piece of code that uses a vulnerability preset on the target system
- Vulnerability: A design, coding, or logic flaw affecting the target system.
- Payload: An exploit takes advantage of a vulnerability. The result of the exploit is the payload
    - i.e: Reverse Shell

#### Modules and Categories ####

- Auxiliary: Any supporting module, such as scanners, crawlers, and fuzzers.

- Encoders: A way of obscuring the payload / exploit to evade signature-based antivirus.

- Evasion: Modules that attempt to assist in the avoidance of anti-virus.

- NOPs: No Operation they do nothing, often used as a buffer to achieve consistent payload sizes.

- Payloads: Code that will run on the target system.
    #### Four Categories Listed Underneath ####
        - Adapters: wraps a single payload to convert them into different formats
            - i.e: A normal payload wrapped inside a powershell adapter (powershell executes the payload)

        - Singles: Self-contained payloads (add user, launch notepad, ect.) do not need additional components to run.

        - Stagers: Setup the connection channel between Metasploit and the target system. Useful when working with staged payloads.
            - Stages Payloads: first uploads a stager on the target system then download the rest of the payload (stage) the inital payload will be small.

        - Stages: Downloaded by the stager. This allows for larger sized payloads.

#### Helpful way of identifying payloads ####

  - ex: generic/shell_reverse_tcp
  - ex: windows/x64/shell/reverse_tcp

- Both are reverse window shells. The first is an inline or (single) payload as indicated by " _ " between "shell" and "reverse".
- The second one is a staged payload as indicated by the " / " between shell and reverse.

